  sodium: 1280 mg
---

Wash and dry all produce. Peel and mince or grate @ginger{1%thumb}. Heat @butter{1%tbsp} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add half the ginger and cook until softened, ~{30-60%seconds}. Add @jasmine rice{1/2%cup}, 3/4 cup water (1 1/2 cups for 4 servings), and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, pat @Regal Springs tilapia{11%ounce} very dry with #paper towels{}. Cut each fillet into four pieces; season all over with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Set aside. Quarter @lime{1}. In a #small bowl{}, combine @mayonnaise{2%tbsp}, @sour cream{2%tbsp}, a squeeze of lime juice, a pinch of salt, and @sriracha{2%tsp} to taste. Add water 1 tsp water at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

In a #large bowl{}, whisk together @sesame oil{1%tbsp}, juice from half the lime, a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tsp}, @sugar{1/2%tsp} (1 tsp for 4 servings), and a pinch of salt and pepper. Add @mixed greens{2%ounce}, @shredded carrots{4%ounce}, and remaining ginger to bowl with dressing; toss to coat. Season generously with salt and pepper. Taste and add more lime juice if desired.

In a second large bowl, combine @tempura mix{82%g}, 1/3 cup cold water (2/3 cup for 4 servings), and 1/2 tsp salt (1 tsp for 4). Heat a 1/3-inch-layer of @vegetable oil{for frying} in a #large heavy-bottomed pan{} over medium-high heat. Patting dry again first if necessary, stir tilapia into batter until fully coated. Line a #plate{} with paper towels.

Once oil is hot enough that a drop of batter sizzles when added to the pan, working in batches if necessary, add coated tilapia. Cook until golden brown on first side, ~{2-3%minutes}; flip with #tongs{} and cook until golden brown on second side and cooked all the way through, ~{2-3%minutes} more. Transfer to paper-towel-lined plate. Immediately season with salt and pepper.

Fluff rice with a #fork{} and season with salt and pepper. Divide between plates with tilapia and salad. Drizzle tilapia with sriracha sauce (or serve on the side for dipping).

> Is there anything better than the light and airy crunch of something tempura-fried? Seriously, you could coat just about anything in that magical Japanese batter and we'd happily chow down. This recipe, though, happens to be extra special. Tilapia fillets turn addictively crispy on the outside and flaky-tender on the inside thanks to the easy technique. On the side, there's a sesame-lime dressed salad and steamy ginger rice. For a finishing touch, the tilapia is topped with a creamy sriracha sauce. There are plenty of fish in the sea, but few as delicious as this!